## Frequently Asked Questions

**Q: Can I use the Work in a commercial product?**
Yes. INOL-1.0 expressly permits commercial use. You may incorporate the Work into products or services you sell or license, provided you comply with the attribution and distribution requirements of this License.

**Q: Do I have to open-source my product if I use the Work?**
No. INOL-1.0 is not a copyleft license. You are not required to release the source code of your own product. You only need to comply with the attribution requirements and include a copy of this License.

**Q: Can I modify the Work without telling anyone?**
You may modify the Work for your own private use without any obligation. However, if you distribute a Modified Work to others, you must include the modification statement required by Section 7.

**Q: What if I only use a small part of the Work?**
The attribution requirements apply regardless of how much of the Work you incorporate. Even if you use only a small component, you must provide the required attribution notice in your distribution.

**Q: Can I use a different license for my product?**
Yes, for your own original code. However, the portions of your product that are derived from the Work must remain governed by INOL-1.0. You may not strip the INOL-1.0 license from the Work-derived portions or relicense them under incompatible terms.

**Q: Can I sublicense the Work?**
You may incorporate the Work into a larger product that you distribute under your own license, but you may not relicense the Work-derived portions themselves. All downstream recipients of the Work-derived portions must be able to exercise their rights under INOL-1.0.

**Q: What does "Prominent Notice" mean in practice?**
A Prominent Notice is one that a reasonable user would find without difficulty. For software, this means a README file, About page, credits section, or documentation page — not a comment buried deep in a rarely-read source file.

**Q: Can I name my product "IdeaNax [Something]"?**
No, not without prior written permission. Using "IdeaNax" as part of your product name implies endorsement or affiliation with IdeaNax, which is not permitted without explicit consent. You may describe your product as "based on IdeaNax's Work" in accordance with the attribution requirements.

**Q: What happens if I accidentally violate the license?**
If you become aware of a violation, you should immediately take steps to cure it (e.g., add the missing attribution notice). Under Section 14.3, you have thirty days to cure a violation after receiving notice from IdeaNax before your license is permanently terminated.

